          "hint": "\n    <div class=\"hint-explanation\">\n      <p class=\"hint-intro\">\n        The ratio of preventive to reactive inspections is a key performance indicator for maintenance \n        maturity. High preventive coverage drives down emergency repairs, extends asset life, and reduces \n        total cost of ownership. Organizations that can measure this split demonstrate visibility into \n        their maintenance practices—the first step toward optimization.\n      </p>\n      \n      <h4 class=\"hint-section-title\">Understanding Your Response Options</h4>\n      \n      <div class=\"s-accordion\">\n        <div class=\"s-accordion-item\">\n          <button class=\"s-accordion-trigger\" type=\"button\">\n            <span class=\"s-accordion-trigger-text\">76-100% (World-class preventive culture)</span>\n            <i class=\"fas fa-chevron-down s-accordion-icon\"></i>\n          </button>\n          <div class=\"s-accordion-panel\">\n            <div class=\"s-accordion-body\">\n              <p>This represents world-class maintenance excellence. The vast majority of your critical assets are inspected on planned schedules before problems develop. Reactive inspections are rare exceptions, typically triggered by unusual events or external damage. Organizations at this level experience minimal unplanned downtime, lower lifecycle costs, and predictable maintenance budgets. This requires mature CMMS usage, strong work planning discipline, and cultural commitment to prevention over firefighting.</p>\n            </div>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n        \n        <div class=\"s-accordion-item\">\n          <button class=\"s-accordion-trigger\" type=\"button\">\n            <span class=\"s-accordion-trigger-text\">51-75% (Solid preventive foundation)</span>\n            <i class=\"fas fa-chevron-down s-accordion-icon\"></i>\n          </button>\n          <div class=\"s-accordion-panel\">\n            <div class=\"s-accordion-body\">\n              <p>You've established a solid preventive foundation. More than half of your critical machinery is on scheduled inspection programs, demonstrating commitment to proactive maintenance. However, 25-49% of assets still operate reactively, meaning you're still dealing with a significant number of unexpected failures. The opportunity is to extend preventive coverage to the remaining assets, particularly those driving reactive maintenance costs.</p>\n            </div>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n        \n        <div class=\"s-accordion-item\">\n          <button class=\"s-accordion-trigger\" type=\"button\">\n            <span class=\"s-accordion-trigger-text\">21-50% (Mixed approach—some preventive, mostly reactive)</span>\n            <i class=\"fas fa-chevron-down s-accordion-icon\"></i>\n          </button>\n          <div class=\"s-accordion-panel\">\n            <div class=\"s-accordion-body\">\n              <p>Your organization is in transition between reactive and preventive maintenance cultures. Some critical assets receive scheduled attention, but the majority are still managed through reactive inspections after problems arise. This creates an unstable operational environment—some equipment is well-maintained while most operates until failure. Maintenance teams spend more time firefighting than preventing, limiting their ability to expand preventive programs.</p>\n            </div>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n        \n        <div class=\"s-accordion-item\">\n          <button class=\"s-accordion-trigger\" type=\"button\">\n            <span class=\"s-accordion-trigger-text\">0-20% (Mostly reactive—inspect only when issues arise)</span>\n            <i class=\"fas fa-chevron-down s-accordion-icon\"></i>\n          </button>\n          <div class=\"s-accordion-panel\">\n            <div class=\"s-accordion-body\">\n              <p>Maintenance operations are predominantly reactive. Only a small fraction of critical assets receive scheduled inspections, while the vast majority are inspected only after failures or performance issues emerge. This approach maximizes emergency repair costs, unplanned downtime, and safety risks. Maintenance teams are constantly firefighting, leaving little capacity for planning or prevention. The business case for shifting toward preventive programs is typically strongest at this maturity level.</p>\n            </div>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n        \n        <div class=\"s-accordion-item\">\n          <button class=\"s-accordion-trigger\" type=\"button\">\n            <span class=\"s-accordion-trigger-text\">Don't track—unable to quantify preventive vs reactive split</span>\n            <i class=\"fas fa-chevron-down s-accordion-icon\"></i>\n          </button>\n          <div class=\"s-accordion-panel\">\n            <div class=\"s-accordion-body\">\n              <p>Your organization lacks visibility into inspection program performance. Without tracking preventive versus reactive work, it's impossible to measure progress, justify preventive investments, or identify which assets need better coverage. This typically indicates absence of CMMS work order classification, or inspections not being formally documented. Establishing this measurement capability is a foundational step toward data-driven maintenance improvement.</p>\n            </div>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n        \n        <div class=\"s-accordion-item\">\n          <button class=\"s-accordion-trigger\" type=\"button\">\n            <span class=\"s-accordion-trigger-text\">Not applicable—all inspections are reactive</span>\n            <i class=\"fas fa-chevron-down s-accordion-icon\"></i>\n          </button>\n          <div class=\"s-accordion-panel\">\n            <div class=\"s-accordion-body\">\n              <p>No scheduled preventive inspections occur. All inspection work is triggered by reported problems, failures, or visible deterioration. This represents the highest-risk maintenance approach, with maximum exposure to unplanned downtime, emergency repair costs, safety incidents, and premature asset replacement. While this may seem cost-effective short-term (no \"wasted\" inspections), research consistently shows reactive-only maintenance costs 3-5x more over asset lifecycles than preventive programs.</p>\n            </div>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  ",
