          "id": "s3_q7",
          "text": "Mean Time Between Failures (MTBF) Tracking",
          "type": "radio",
          "subtitle": "Do you measure and analyze MTBF to optimize maintenance intervals and identify chronic problem assets?",
          "hint": "\n    <div class=\"hint-explanation\">\n      <p class=\"hint-intro\">\n        MTBF analysis transforms maintenance from calendar-based routines to intelligent, data-driven \n        schedules. By measuring time between asset failures, you identify which equipment is unreliable, \n        whether maintenance intervals are too long or too short, and where design or operational changes \n        could prevent recurring problems. Organizations that track MTBF continuously improve; those that \n        don't repeat the same failures endlessly.\n      </p>\n      \n      <h4 class=\"hint-section-title\">Understanding Your Response Options</h4>\n      \n      <div class=\"s-accordion\">\n        <div class=\"s-accordion-item\">\n          <button class=\"s-accordion-trigger\" type=\"button\">\n            <span class=\"s-accordion-trigger-text\">Yes—systematic MTBF analysis drives preventive maintenance optimization</span>\n            <i class=\"fas fa-chevron-down s-accordion-icon\"></i>\n          </button>\n          <div class=\"s-accordion-panel\">\n            <div class=\"s-accordion-body\">\n              <p>This represents reliability engineering excellence. Your organization systematically calculates MTBF for critical assets by tracking failure events and operating hours/cycles. This data drives maintenance optimization: if pumps average 8,000 hours between failures but preventive maintenance occurs every 4,000 hours, you're over-maintaining and wasting resources. Conversely, if failures occur every 2,000 hours but PM is scheduled every 6,000 hours, you're under-maintaining and experiencing preventable failures. MTBF analysis identifies chronic problem assets requiring redesign, replacement, or root cause investigation. You track trends over time to verify that maintenance improvements actually increase reliability. This quantitative approach supports Reliability-Centered Maintenance (RCM) and demonstrates continuous improvement culture.</p>\n            </div>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n        \n        <div class=\"s-accordion-item\">\n          <button class=\"s-accordion-trigger\" type=\"button\">\n            <span class=\"s-accordion-trigger-text\">Partially—track failure patterns informally but no formal MTBF calculations</span>\n            <i class=\"fas fa-chevron-down s-accordion-icon\"></i>\n          </button>\n          <div class=\"s-accordion-panel\">\n            <div class=\"s-accordion-body\">\n              <p>Your team is aware of failure patterns through experience and observation—\"those pumps seem to fail every few months,\" \"we replace those bearings constantly.\" This institutional knowledge provides value and indicates failure awareness. However, without quantitative MTBF calculations, you can't optimize precisely. Informal awareness becomes \"that equipment is unreliable\" without knowing whether it fails every 500 hours or 5,000 hours, preventing evidence-based decisions about maintenance intervals or replacement timing. Pattern recognition exists but lacks the rigor to drive systematic improvement or justify investments in better equipment or more frequent maintenance.</p>\n            </div>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n        \n        <div class=\"s-accordion-item\">\n          <button class=\"s-accordion-trigger\" type=\"button\">\n            <span class=\"s-accordion-trigger-text\">Aware of repeat failures but lack quantitative analysis</span>\n            <i class=\"fas fa-chevron-down s-accordion-icon\"></i>\n          </button>\n          <div class=\"s-accordion-panel\">\n            <div class=\"s-accordion-body\">\n              <p>When the same asset fails repeatedly, people notice and complain—\"we just fixed that last month!\" This awareness creates frustration but doesn't drive improvement without quantitative analysis. You know some assets are \"problem children\" but can't distinguish between truly unreliable equipment and assets operating under harsh conditions that need more frequent maintenance. Without MTBF data, you can't answer questions like \"Is this asset worse than industry average?\" or \"Would replacement pay for itself in reduced maintenance costs?\" Awareness without measurement prevents evolution from reactive response to proactive prevention.</p>\n            </div>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n        \n        <div class=\"s-accordion-item\">\n          <button class=\"s-accordion-trigger\" type=\"button\">\n            <span class=\"s-accordion-trigger-text\">Focus on correcting failures rather than analyzing patterns</span>\n            <i class=\"fas fa-chevron-down s-accordion-icon\"></i>\n          </button>\n          <div class=\"s-accordion-panel\">\n            <div class=\"s-accordion-body\">\n              <p>All maintenance effort goes into fixing failures as they occur, with no systematic attempt to understand why failures happen, how frequently they occur, or what patterns exist. Each failure is treated as an isolated event requiring immediate repair, then forgotten once fixed. This reactive approach ensures repeated mistakes—the same failure modes recur indefinitely because root causes are never investigated. Resources are wasted addressing symptoms rather than identifying systemic issues. Equipment that should be replaced continues failing and consuming maintenance dollars. Maintenance intervals aren't optimized because nobody knows actual failure rates. This represents the lowest maturity level of maintenance management.</p>\n            </div>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n        \n        <div class=\"s-accordion-item\">\n          <button class=\"s-accordion-trigger\" type=\"button\">\n            <span class=\"s-accordion-trigger-text\">No failure pattern tracking or analysis</span>\n            <i class=\"fas fa-chevron-down s-accordion-icon\"></i>\n          </button>\n          <div class=\"s-accordion-panel\">\n            <div class=\"s-accordion-body\">\n              <p>Failures are addressed as they occur but not tracked or analyzed in any systematic way. There's no organizational learning from failure history—each generation of technicians rediscovers the same problems. You cannot answer basic reliability questions: \"Which asset types are most unreliable?\" \"Are failures increasing or decreasing over time?\" \"What's the typical lifespan of this equipment?\" Without failure data, preventive maintenance schedules are arbitrary guesses rather than evidence-based intervals. This eliminates any path toward predictive maintenance or reliability improvement and ensures maximum lifetime costs through repeated preventable failures.</p>\n            </div>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n        \n        <div class=\"s-accordion-item\">\n          <button class=\"s-accordion-trigger\" type=\"button\">\n            <span class=\"s-accordion-trigger-text\">Not applicable—minimal equipment failures occur</span>\n            <i class=\"fas fa-chevron-down s-accordion-icon\"></i>\n          </button>\n          <div class=\"s-accordion-panel\">\n            <div class=\"s-accordion-body\">\n              <p>Your equipment experiences very few failures, making MTBF analysis statistically meaningless. This could indicate two very different situations: either you have an excellent preventive maintenance program that successfully prevents failures before they occur (ideal state), or you have relatively new equipment with insufficient operational history to have experienced normal failure patterns yet (transitional state). If the former, your preventive program is working exactly as intended—MTBF is high because failures are rare. If the latter, establish failure tracking systems now so when equipment ages and failures begin, you'll have baseline data for analysis and optimization.</p>\n            </div>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  ",
